05-basic-data-types/basic-data-types-01.cpp<pre><code>#include &lt;iomanip&gt; // std::setprecision
#include &lt;ios&gt; // std::fixed
#include &lt;iostream&gt; // std::cin/cout

int
main(int, char *[]) {
    int i;
    long l;
    char c;
    float f;
    double d;

    std::cin &gt;&gt; i &gt;&gt; l &gt;&gt; c &gt;&gt; f &gt;&gt; d;

    std::cout &lt;&lt; i &lt;&lt; std::endl;
    std::cout &lt;&lt; l &lt;&lt; std::endl;
    std::cout &lt;&lt; c &lt;&lt; std::endl;
    std::cout &lt;&lt; std::fixed &lt;&lt; std::setprecision(3) &lt;&lt; f &lt;&lt; std::endl;
    std::cout &lt;&lt; std::fixed &lt;&lt; std::setprecision(9) &lt;&lt; d &lt;&lt; std::endl;

    return 0;
}
</code></pre> <p>We simply create some variables of the following types: <code>int</code>, <code>long</code>, <code>char</code>, <code>float</code> and <code>double</code>, read from <code>std::cin</code> and output to <code>std::cout</code>. <code>float</code> and <code>double</code> have some manipulation to with a fixed number of decimals each, namely 3 and 9.</p> <p>A simple replacement of this approach with five <code>std::istream_iterator&lt;T&gt;</code> and another set of five <code>std::ostream_iterator&lt;type, “\n”&gt;</code> is for sure not the kind of challenge we are looking for, even if one of the goals is to use iterators here, there and everywhere. Let us therefore skip putting that in written form.</p>

05-basic-data-types/basic-data-types-03.cpp<pre><code>#include &lt;algorithm&gt; // std::copy_n
#include &lt;iomanip&gt; // std::setprecision
#include &lt;ios&gt; // std::fixed
#include &lt;iostream&gt; // std::cin/cout
#include &lt;iterator&gt; // std::ostream_iterator/istream
#include &lt;utility&gt; // std::make_pair

template &lt;typename BasicType&gt;
auto
in_out() {
    auto in = std::istream_iterator&lt;BasicType&gt;{std::cin};
    auto out = std::ostream_iterator&lt;BasicType&gt;{std::cout, "\n"};
    return std::make_pair(in, out);
}

template&lt;typename BasicType&gt;
auto
for_each(size_t /* fprec */ = 3, size_t /* dprec */ = 9) {
    auto [in, out] = in_out&lt;BasicType&gt;();
    std::copy_n(in, 1, out); // *out++ = *in;
}

template&lt;typename BasicType&gt;
auto
for_each_floating(size_t prec) {
    const auto def_prec{std::cout.precision()}; // save current prec
    const auto def_flags{std::cout.flags()}; // save current prec
    std::cout &lt;&lt; std::fixed &lt;&lt; std::setprecision(prec);
    auto [in, out] = in_out&lt;BasicType&gt;();
    std::copy_n(in, 1, out); // *out++ = *in;
    (std::cout &lt;&lt; std::setprecision(def_prec)).flags(def_flags); // reset
}

template&lt;&gt;
auto
for_each&lt;float&gt;(size_t fprec /* = 3 */, size_t /* dprec = 9 */) {
    for_each_floating&lt;float&gt;(fprec);
}

template&lt;&gt;
auto
for_each&lt;double&gt;(size_t /* fprec = 3 */, size_t dprec /* = 9 */) {
    for_each_floating&lt;double&gt;(dprec);
}

template&lt;typename BasicType, typename BasicType2, typename ...BasicTypes&gt;
auto
for_each(size_t fprec = 3, size_t dprec = 9) {
    for_each&lt;BasicType&gt;(fprec, dprec);
    for_each&lt;BasicType2, BasicTypes...&gt;(fprec, dprec);
}

int
main(int, char *[]) {
    for_each&lt;int, long, char, float, double&gt;();
    return 0;
}
</code></pre> <p>This is our best try. A function <code>in_out</code> serves as a central factory for the <code>std::istream_iterator</code> / <code>std::ostream_iterator</code> pair we need. And the management of the <code>float</code> / <code>double</code> precision differences is also outsourced to a <code>for_each_floating</code> function.</p> <p>But that is all. The recursive template nature and the specializations are still there. There has to be something more modern than this.</p>
